snippet.textDisplay:
Edit: forgot to say. Every Hair stylist has ALWAYS started at my roots too. I wouldn’t know that’s wasn’t ok until Brad told me.

What do I have to do to get a “real” hair color professional like Brad to do my hair?? I’m a natural blonde that gets blonde highlights. Just so I have dimension. And it’s never good!! I’ve tried so many salons, so many stylists. When brad said “do you think we go into the back and mix box dye”. That’s exactly what I think some of these “professionals” do. I just paid $160 a few days ago and she didn’t even tone my hair after. Just rinsed and blowed dried. I did learn a few years ago to specifically ask for a color specialist. Nope, doesn’t matter where I live. how do they mess up blonde highlights on a blonde 😭 😭

snippet.textDisplay: I love orange hair! I had orange hair for October. I’m hoping you or someone in the comments can help me with something. I went blonde a few weeks ago and chopped about six inches off to celebrate getting a new job. I was expecting a blonde with violet undertones (I used the clairol true color line and mixed a 6AV with a 10AV). I feel like it turned out very ashy (my base was a really light blonde with slight yellow tones, I’d say about a level 10 or 11). I would like to use purple shampoo, but I’m very worried that my hair will turn green. Could I use a red semi permanent on wet hair as a toner and rinse after a minute or two? Or will my hair be fine with a purple shampoo? I’ve never been a legit blonde before(aka rocked piss yellow hair, never used toner, never used purple shampoo 🤣). Would appreciate feedback 💜 p.s I’ve been binge watching your videos since I discovered you on Facebook ❤️

snippet.textDisplay: What is your opinion on Henna / Mehendi? Before you're confused by Google search, let me tell you Henna is a natural dye obtained from Henna plants leaf and has been used for dying  hair and hands / feet since ancient times. It's famous in India and Arab countries as it can naturally color your hair black/ brown / red / orange if you master it's composition. It's commonly used in my family as a hair mask as it helps with dandruff and helps strengthen and nourish the hair. The only down side is it's cold properties, so if you're easily susceptible to a cold, you might need some precautions. As for genral public like me, as long as I give myself ample sunlight after the wash, it'll be fine. Just wash off Henna early morning and sun dry your hair and it'll all be fine. This has been in our family for generations and am totally fine with it. Unless you get a chemically formulated version of Henna whose effects entirely depends on their composition. Would like to know your opinion as a non asian
